"""
rel_health — the reliability-engine observability sink (design §7 "rel_health.spl
— the observability sink"; architecture §5 "Observability"; design §9 lane L2).

Contract: doc/05_design/hardware/nand_recovery/recovery_algorithms_design.md §7
(implements architecture doc reliability_engine_architecture.md §5). This is the
durable sink mounted at `RelFtlMount.health` (design §1.4): every other policy
lane (`rel_ladder`, `rel_vref`, `rel_refresh`, `rel_disturb`, `rel_wear`) and the
wiring pass (§7 `rel_tick_select`) reads it for triggers; nothing here holds a
Fil/Ftl handle or actuates anything — pure functions over `RelHealth` (declared
in rel_types.spl, §1.3), return-the-object on every mutator (design §0
"Return-the-object").

Pure-policy leaf (design §0 / guide "rel_* implementation wave"): imports ONLY
nvme_types.* + nd_types.* + rel_types.* — never fil/ftl (the mounts in fil/ftl
import this module, not the reverse; import-graph law).

Coarse-bucket honesty (architecture §5, task instruction to name the
distinction): `corrected` fed into `rel_health_note_read` is the coarse
`FilRead.corrected` bucket (0 clean / 1 corrected / 2+ uncorrectable) — an
EVENT count, not a per-bit magnitude. `rel_health_rber` therefore reports a
corrected-EVENT rate (events / reads, scaled to ppm units so it stays an
i64), not true bit-RBER. On the NandEmu backend (prereq 1b) that bucket
reflects a modeled per-read bit count; on backends without it, it is an event
flag only. Callers/specs must not present this as true bit-RBER (architecture
§5: "Name the distinction in specs — do not present event-rate as true
bit-RBER").

Cause tags (design §7; owned by this lane — `RelHealth.refresh_cause`'s
values, per rel_types.spl:140 "constants in L2"): `rel_cause_none` (no
refresh cause / just erased), `rel_cause_age` (FCR — age-triggered),
`rel_cause_err` (DEAR — error-trend-triggered), `rel_cause_dist` (STRAW —
disturb-triggered). `rel_health_mark_cause` records which fired; distinct
codes so a spec can assert *why* a rewrite happened (architecture §5
"Refresh cause tags").

Erase-reset discipline (design §7 "Erase-reset discipline"): a block's
reliability state must not survive a P/E cycle. `rel_health_on_erase` clears
`corrected_events`, `retry_depth_max`, and `refresh_cause` for exactly the
erased block — `reads` and `corrected_sum` (the RBER denominator/numerator)
are DELIBERATELY left alone (not part of the design's erase-reset list; RBER
is a lifetime-of-block estimate, not a since-last-erase one). Without this
reset a refreshed-then-recycled block keeps a stale
`corrected_events >= REL_REFRESH_ERR_EVENTS` and its first corrected read
would immediately re-fire refresh — a sticky FCR trigger.

Landmines honored (design §0 / guide "Language landmines"):
- i64-first, no float (rber is scaled-ppm integer division).
- Return-the-object: every mutator copies `h` into `var out = h` and returns
  `out`; arrays are value types so the copy is independent of the input.
- Per-block state is a dense [i64] array of length NUM_BLOCKS, indexed by the
  raw block index — the design §7 pseudocode signatures take `blk: i64`
  (matches rel_types.spl's typed-dims note: the array itself stays [i64]
  because the block is the ARRAY INDEX, a flat i64; only RelBlockObs.blk and
  RelLadderState.blk are the typed NdBlock scalar fields). Callers holding an
  NdBlock convert at this flat-index boundary (`blk.idx`), per the guide's
  TYPED DIMENSIONS LAW.
- Cause/kind codes are fn-returning literals, never module-level collection
  initializers (freestanding-safe).
"""

use nvme_types.*
use nd_types.*
use rel_types.*

# ── Cause tags (design §7; this lane owns RelHealth.refresh_cause's values) ───
fn rel_cause_none() -> i64:
    0              # no refresh cause (default / just erased)

fn rel_cause_age() -> i64:
    1              # FCR: age-triggered refresh

fn rel_cause_err() -> i64:
    2              # DEAR: error-trend-triggered refresh

fn rel_cause_dist() -> i64:
    3              # STRAW: disturb-triggered refresh

# ── Sink fns (design §7 pseudocode, implemented verbatim) ─────────────────────

# Fold one read's outcome into the durable sink: bump the read count, add the
# coarse corrected bucket into the running sum (RBER numerator), bump the
# corrected-EVENT counter iff this read needed correction, and track the
# deepest recovery-ladder rung this block has ever needed.
fn rel_health_note_read(h: RelHealth, blk: i64, corrected: i64, depth: i64) -> RelHealth:
    var out = h
    out.reads[blk] = h.reads[blk] + 1
    out.corrected_sum[blk] = h.corrected_sum[blk] + corrected
    if corrected >= 1:
        out.corrected_events[blk] = h.corrected_events[blk] + 1
    if depth > h.retry_depth_max[blk]:
        out.retry_depth_max[blk] = depth
    return out

# RBER estimate: corrected-EVENTS / reads, scaled to ppm (x1_000_000) so the
# result stays an exact i64 ratio with no float. 0 reads -> 0 (no divide-by-
# zero). This is an event-rate estimator (architecture §5 honesty note above),
# not a modeled bit-rate unless the NandEmu shadow-word seam (prereq 1b) is the
# backend feeding `corrected`.
fn rel_health_rber(h: RelHealth, blk: i64) -> i64:
    if h.reads[blk] == 0:
        return 0
    (h.corrected_sum[blk] * 1000000) / h.reads[blk]

# Record which cause fired the most recent refresh for this block (one of the
# rel_cause_* tags above), so a spec/observer can assert *why* a rewrite
# happened.
fn rel_health_mark_cause(h: RelHealth, blk: i64, cause: i64) -> RelHealth:
    var out = h
    out.refresh_cause[blk] = cause
    return out

# Erase-reset discipline: clear exactly this block's per-cycle reliability
# state so a recycled block doesn't sticky-refresh on its first corrected
# read. reads/corrected_sum (the lifetime RBER estimate) are untouched — call
# from the erase/reclaim path, parallel to rel_vref_decay_on_erase and
# rel_disturb_clear (design §7 "Erase-reset discipline").
fn rel_health_on_erase(h: RelHealth, blk: i64) -> RelHealth:
    var out = h
    out.corrected_events[blk] = 0
    out.retry_depth_max[blk] = 0
    out.refresh_cause[blk] = rel_cause_none()
    return out
